<div id="review_445629821" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/445629821" />
    <a title="Gene" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/9340136-gene"><img alt="Gene" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1544797852p2/9340136.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/445629821?book_show_action=true">Oct 31, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Gene" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Gene" href="/user/show/9340136-gene">Gene</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/9340136-gene?shelf=hercule-poirot">hercule-poirot</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/9340136-gene?shelf=crime-and-mystery">crime-and-mystery</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer445629821" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10763153153141649270"><b>Review updated on April 11, 2019.</b><br/><br/>The first case of Hercule Poirot. <br/><img src='https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1555029277i/27350455._SX540_.jpg' alt='Hercule Poirot' class='gr-hostedUserImg'/><br/>He is a Belgian just immigrated to England. Nothing about him makes him look like one of the greatest detectives ever. The woman who helped him settle in his new country was poisoned, Poirot is forced to use his &quot;grey cells&quot; for the first time (but definitely not for the last time). An expected from Agatha Christie crazily complicated mystery full of twists and surprises follow. <br/><br/>Agatha Christie wrote this novel as a bet that she </span>
  <span id="freeText10763153153141649270" style="display:none"><b>Review updated on April 11, 2019.</b><br><br>The first case of Hercule Poirot. <br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1555029277i/27350455._SX540_.jpg" alt="Hercule Poirot" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br>He is a Belgian just immigrated to England. Nothing about him makes him look like one of the greatest detectives ever. The woman who helped him settle in his new country was poisoned, Poirot is forced to use his "grey cells" for the first time (but definitely not for the last time). An expected from Agatha Christie crazily complicated mystery full of twists and surprises follow. <br><br>Agatha Christie wrote this novel as a bet that she can write a mystery novel with all the clues given to readers, which still will be really hard to figure out before the book (Poirot in this case) explains it all. As a result of this simple bet the greatest woman mystery writer was born. She also holds a record as the all-time bestselling writer. As well as world greatest detectives: #2 (Hercule Poirot; Sherlock Holmes holds #1 for me) and #3 (Miss Marple; shares this place with Nero Wolfe - in my opinion). Not as strong as her later books, the novel still belongs to top classic mystery works.<br><br>I already mentioned Sherlock Holmes. As far as characters go Hercule Poirot is equally colorful, interesting, and crazy: like all geniuses. <br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1555031374i/27350544.jpg" alt="Sherlock Holmes" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br>When it comes to sidekicks Dr. Watson wins however. While he is not the smartest guy around, Captain Hastings beats him as a guy having his IQ in single digits. It does not prevent him from being an excellent chronicler of Poirot's investigations. <br><br>Speaking about investigations, when it comes to creating a complicated mystery with all the clues given to readers and still being insanely hard to figure out, if anybody can do it better than Agatha Christie I have not found such person yet. I have been looking for a long time - right after I realized I had read everything the lady wrote. Nobody comes anywhere close to her. <br><br>Something else I realized during my second read. I thought after you read Christie's book once and learned whodunit it is not fun to reread it. I could not be farther from the truth. During my reread I remembered who the culprit was, but not the details. These details kept me practically on the edge of the seat the second time around. Somehow Christie could make all the clues, twists, etc. coming non-stop and in the most exciting manner. Once again I do not know anybody who does it better. <br><br>At this point I will stop. It should be obvious that the rating is good. Only some slight lack of refining present in later books prevent me from going all the way to 5 stars. <br><br>P.S. Most of the time when you see a depiction of your beloved character in a movie, or a mini-series you complain that they completely missed the mark. David Suchet nailed Poirot. The first time I saw him playing the role I was sure he was a fragment of my imagination coming to life. He was that good: see the first picture.</span>
  <a data-text-id="10763153153141649270" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


