<div id="review_2538009668" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2538009668" />
    <a title="Mary Deacon" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/67949588-mary-deacon"><img alt="Mary Deacon" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1495311020p2/67949588.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2538009668?book_show_action=true">Sep 24, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Mary Deacon" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Mary Deacon" href="/user/show/67949588-mary-deacon">Mary Deacon</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2538009668" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10163778226174218320">The Mysterious Affair at Styles is Agatha Christies first published novel and the introduction of Poirot to the world. While it suffers from the fact that Poirot is not the calm and methodical detective he would later become it soars in the plotting and intricacy of the mystery. What would seem to be a straightforward murder mystery becomes a tangled web of clues - a Christie trait that she establishes from the very beginning. Moreover, just as she would later make her trademark, all the clues a</span>
  <span id="freeText10163778226174218320" style="display:none">The Mysterious Affair at Styles is Agatha Christies first published novel and the introduction of Poirot to the world. While it suffers from the fact that Poirot is not the calm and methodical detective he would later become it soars in the plotting and intricacy of the mystery. What would seem to be a straightforward murder mystery becomes a tangled web of clues - a Christie trait that she establishes from the very beginning. Moreover, just as she would later make her trademark, all the clues are there in front of the reader. It takes the mind of Poirot to put them together. This is a "MUST READ!"</span>
  <a data-text-id="10163778226174218320" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


